('salade_de_plantain_gabonese', 'Salade de Plantain', 105, 1.2, 27.0, 0.4, 2.5, 10.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['salade de plantain', 'with onion vinaigrette', 'with tomato'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sliced boiled plantain served cool with a simple dressing of onions and vinegar constitutes a refreshing salad eaten as a light meal or side dish in Gabonese households.', TRUE),
('fruit_a_pain_breadfruit_gabonese', 'Fruit à Pain (Breadfruit)', 103, 1.1, 27.1, 0.2, 4.9, 11.0, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['fruit à pain (breadfruit)', 'roasted', 'boiled', 'fried'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Breadfruit is roasted, boiled, or fried and eaten as a starchy side dish in coastal and island areas of Gabon. It is a valued food security crop with a potato-like texture when cooked.', TRUE),
('pomme_de_terre_bouillie_boiled_potato_gabonese', 'Pomme de Terre Bouillie (Boiled Potato)', 87, 1.9, 20.1, 0.1, 1.8, 0.9, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['pomme de terre bouillie (boiled potato)', 'plain', 'with butter'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Boiled potatoes were introduced during the colonial era and are now common in urban Gabonese households and restaurants, typically served as a Western-style side dish.', TRUE),
('pomme_de_terre_frite_french_fries_gabonese', 'Pomme de Terre Frite (French Fries)', 312, 3.4, 41.4, 14.9, 3.8, 0.3, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['pomme de terre frite (french fries)', 'thick cut', 'thin cut', 'seasoned'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'French fries are extremely popular in Libreville and major Gabonese cities, served alongside grilled meats and sandwiches in restaurants, fast food stalls, and homes.', TRUE),
('riz_blanc_cuit_cooked_white_rice_gabonese', 'Riz Blanc Cuit (Cooked White Rice)', 130, 2.7, 28.2, 0.3, 0.4, 0.0, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['riz blanc cuit (cooked white rice)', 'long grain', 'jasmine'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Steamed white rice is a daily staple in virtually every Gabonese household, forming the base for sauces, stews, and grilled accompaniments throughout the country.', TRUE),
('baguette_francaise_gabonese', 'Baguette Française', 270, 9.0, 53.0, 1.2, 2.3, 2.0, 100, 250, 'research', ARRAY['baguette française', 'plain', 'with butter', 'with sardines'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'The French baguette remains central to daily life in Gabon, eaten at breakfast and throughout the day. Bakeries producing fresh baguettes are a ubiquitous feature of Gabonese towns.', TRUE),
('pain_complet_whole_wheat_bread_gabonese', 'Pain Complet (Whole Wheat Bread)', 247, 8.5, 48.0, 3.2, 6.0, 3.5, 100, 35, 'research', ARRAY['pain complet (whole wheat bread)', 'sliced', 'loaf'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Whole wheat bread is available in Libreville bakeries and supermarkets catering to health-conscious consumers and expatriates seeking nutritional variety beyond the baguette.', TRUE),
('makala_fried_dough_balls_gabonese', 'Makala (Fried Dough Balls)', 342, 5.5, 48.0, 14.5, 1.2, 4.0, 100, 40, 'research', ARRAY['makala (fried dough balls)', 'plain', 'sweetened', 'with vanilla'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Makala are deep-fried dough balls made from wheat flour and are sold by street vendors throughout Gabon. They are eaten for breakfast or as snacks with tea, coffee, or soft drinks.', TRUE),
('beignets_sucres_sweet_fritters_gabonese', 'Beignets Sucrés (Sweet Fritters)', 355, 5.8, 50.5, 14.8, 1.0, 12.0, 100, 35, 'research', ARRAY['beignets sucrés (sweet fritters)', 'plain', 'with jam', 'with condensed milk'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sweet fried dough fritters are a breakfast staple sold by vendors at roadsides and markets across Gabon. They are made fresh each morning and eaten warm with sweetened condensed milk.', TRUE),
('mandazi_east_african_style_doughnuts_gabonese', 'Mandazi (East African-Style Doughnuts)', 338, 6.2, 52.0, 12.0, 1.5, 8.0, 100, 45, 'research', ARRAY['mandazi (east african-style doughnuts)', 'plain', 'coconut-flavored', 'cardamom-spiced'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Mandazi-style fried breads are found in Gabon through Central African trade networks and diaspora communities. They are mildly sweet, triangular or oval, and eaten as breakfast or snacks.', TRUE),
('crepes_gabonaises_gabonese', 'Crêpes Gabonaises', 210, 6.5, 30.0, 7.5, 0.8, 4.5, 120, 60, 'research', ARRAY['crêpes gabonaises', 'with butter and sugar', 'with jam', 'with condensed milk'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Thin crêpes influenced by French culinary tradition are popular for Sunday breakfast and special occasions in Gabon. They are served with butter, jam, honey, or sweetened condensed milk.', TRUE),
('crepes_epaisses_thick_pancakes_gabonese', 'Crêpes Épaisses (Thick Pancakes)', 230, 7.0, 33.0, 8.5, 0.9, 5.5, 150, 75, 'research', ARRAY['crêpes épaisses (thick pancakes)', 'with maple syrup', 'with banana', 'with chocolate'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Thicker American-style pancakes have become popular in Libreville cafés and modern breakfast spots alongside the traditional French crêpe. They are served with syrup and fruit.', TRUE),
('omelette_nature_gabonese', 'Omelette Nature', 154, 10.5, 1.0, 12.0, 0.0, 0.5, 120, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['omelette nature', 'plain', 'with salt and pepper'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'A plain two-egg omelette is a staple quick breakfast or light meal in Gabonese households and roadside restaurants. It is simple, affordable, and widely available.', TRUE),
('omelette_tomates_oignons_gabonese', 'Omelette Tomates-Oignons', 165, 10.8, 4.2, 11.8, 0.8, 2.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['omelette tomates-oignons', 'with chili', 'without chili'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Omelette filled with diced tomatoes and onions is one of the most popular breakfast dishes in Gabon, served with bread or baguette at home and in small eateries.', TRUE),
('omelette_aux_herbes_gabonese', 'Omelette Aux Herbes', 160, 10.5, 1.5, 12.2, 0.3, 0.5, 120, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['omelette aux herbes', 'with parsley', 'with chives', 'with local herbs'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Herb omelette with parsley, chives, or local herbs reflects French culinary influence in Gabonese cooking. It is a popular option in cafés and upscale breakfast spots.', TRUE),
('omelette_mixte_mixed_omelette_gabonese', 'Omelette Mixte (Mixed Omelette)', 195, 12.0, 4.5, 14.5, 0.5, 1.8, 180, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['omelette mixte (mixed omelette)', 'with vegetables', 'with sardines', 'with chicken'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'A filled omelette with vegetables, onions, peppers, and sometimes meat or fish is a hearty breakfast or light meal widely sold in Gabonese canteens and small restaurants.', TRUE),
('ufs_brouilles_scrambled_eggs_gabonese', 'Œufs Brouillés (Scrambled Eggs)', 148, 10.0, 1.2, 11.5, 0.0, 0.5, 120, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['œufs brouillés (scrambled eggs)', 'plain', 'with onions', 'with tomatoes'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Scrambled eggs are a common breakfast preparation in urban Gabon, reflecting French influence. They are often served with baguette and butter or alongside fried plantain.', TRUE),
('ufs_au_plat_fried_eggs_gabonese', 'Œufs au Plat (Fried Eggs)', 196, 12.7, 0.8, 15.8, 0.0, 0.4, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['œufs au plat (fried eggs)', 'sunny-side up', 'over easy', 'in palm oil'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Fried eggs are a versatile everyday dish eaten at breakfast, lunch, and dinner in Gabon. They are typically cooked in palm oil or vegetable oil with a runny or set yolk.', TRUE),
('ufs_durs_hard_boiled_eggs_gabonese', 'Œufs Durs (Hard-Boiled Eggs)', 155, 12.6, 1.1, 10.6, 0.0, 0.5, 100, 50, 'research', ARRAY['œufs durs (hard-boiled eggs)', 'plain', 'with salt', 'sliced in salad'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Hard-boiled eggs are sold by street vendors and eaten as a protein-rich snack or breakfast alongside baguettes throughout Gabon. They are often seasoned with salt and pepper.', TRUE),
('ufs_a_la_coque_soft_boiled_eggs_gabonese', 'Œufs à la Coque (Soft-Boiled Eggs)', 143, 12.5, 0.7, 9.9, 0.0, 0.4, 100, 50, 'research', ARRAY['œufs à la coque (soft-boiled eggs)', 'with toast', 'plain'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Soft-boiled eggs served with toast soldiers are a French-influenced breakfast dish found in Libreville homes and upscale hotels, reflecting the country''s colonial culinary heritage.', TRUE),
('fromage_de_chevre_frais_fresh_goat_cheese_gabonese', 'Fromage de Chèvre Frais (Fresh Goat Cheese)', 264, 14.0, 3.5, 21.3, 0.0, 2.0, 50, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['fromage de chèvre frais (fresh goat cheese)', 'plain', 'with herbs'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Fresh goat cheese is produced locally in Gabon by small-scale farmers and is increasingly available in urban markets. It is eaten on bread or in salads by health-conscious urban consumers.', TRUE),
('yaourt_nature_plain_yogurt_gabonese', 'Yaourt Nature (Plain Yogurt)', 61, 3.5, 4.7, 3.3, 0.0, 4.7, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['yaourt nature (plain yogurt)', 'full fat', 'low fat'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Plain yogurt is available in Gabonese supermarkets and is consumed as a breakfast food or healthy snack. Local dairy production supplements imported French and regional brands.', TRUE),
('yaourt_fruite_fruit_yogurt_gabonese', 'Yaourt Fruité (Fruit Yogurt)', 95, 3.2, 16.5, 2.5, 0.2, 14.0, 125, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['yaourt fruité (fruit yogurt)', 'mango', 'passion fruit', 'strawberry', 'banana'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Fruit-flavored yogurts in various flavors including mango, passion fruit, and strawberry are popular convenience foods available in supermarkets across Gabonese cities.', TRUE),
('beurre_butter_gabonese', 'Beurre (Butter)', 717, 0.9, 0.1, 81.0, 0.0, 0.1, 10, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['beurre (butter)', 'salted', 'unsalted'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Butter imported primarily from France and other European countries is used daily in Gabonese households for spreading on baguettes and cooking. It is a marker of French culinary influence.', TRUE),
('lait_entier_whole_milk_gabonese', 'Lait Entier (Whole Milk)', 61, 3.2, 4.8, 3.3, 0.0, 5.1, 250, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['lait entier (whole milk)', 'fresh', 'uht', 'pasteurized'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Fresh whole milk is consumed in Gabon primarily as an imported or UHT product, used in coffee, tea, and cooking. Local fresh milk production remains limited but growing.', TRUE),
('lait_concentre_sucre_sweetened_condensed_milk_gabonese', 'Lait Concentré Sucré (Sweetened Condensed Milk)', 321, 7.9, 54.4, 8.7, 0.0, 54.4, 50, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['lait concentré sucré (sweetened condensed milk)', 'full fat', 'reduced fat'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sweetened condensed milk is extensively used in Gabon to sweeten coffee, tea, and is poured over crêpes, bread, and desserts. It is an affordable pantry staple across all income levels.', TRUE),
('creme_fraiche_gabonese', 'Crème Fraîche', 292, 2.1, 3.4, 30.0, 0.0, 2.8, 30, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['crème fraîche', 'full fat', 'light'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Crème fraîche imported from France is used in French-style cooking in Gabon, particularly in sauces and soups prepared in urban households and upscale restaurants.', TRUE),
('fromage_fondu_processed_cheese_gabonese', 'Fromage Fondu (Processed Cheese)', 260, 14.0, 8.0, 19.5, 0.0, 3.5, 30, 18, 'research', ARRAY['fromage fondu (processed cheese)', 'plain', 'with herbs', 'light'], 'dairy', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Processed cheese triangles (like La Vache Qui Rit) are enormously popular in Gabon, eaten spread on baguettes for breakfast and snacks. They are widely available at all price points.', TRUE),
('poivrons_sautes_sauteed_bell_peppers_gabonese', 'Poivrons Sautés (Sautéed Bell Peppers)', 46, 1.2, 8.5, 1.5, 1.8, 5.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['poivrons sautés (sautéed bell peppers)', 'red pepper', 'mixed peppers', 'green pepper'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Colorful bell peppers sautéed with onions and garlic are used as a side dish and condiment base in Gabonese cooking. Red, yellow, and green peppers are all available in urban markets.', TRUE),
('oignons_caramelises_caramelized_onions_gabonese', 'Oignons Caramélisés (Caramelized Onions)', 88, 1.5, 18.0, 2.5, 1.8, 13.5, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['oignons caramélisés (caramelized onions)', 'with oil', 'with butter'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Slowly caramelized onions are used as a flavorful condiment and garnish in Gabonese French-influenced cooking, added to meats, sandwiches, and sauces.', TRUE),
('tomates_concassees_crushed_tomatoes_gabonese', 'Tomates Concassées (Crushed Tomatoes)', 32, 1.5, 6.5, 0.3, 1.8, 4.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['tomates concassées (crushed tomatoes)', 'with onion', 'with garlic', 'with chili'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Crushed or roughly chopped tomatoes cooked down with onions and seasonings form the base sauce for countless Gabonese dishes, from rice to grilled meats.', TRUE),
('puree_de_tomates_maison_gabonese', 'Purée de Tomates Maison', 35, 1.6, 7.5, 0.3, 1.9, 5.0, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['purée de tomates maison', 'plain', 'spiced'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Homemade tomato purée cooked with onions, garlic, and spices is an essential cooking base in Gabonese kitchens, used to start most savory dishes.', TRUE),
('sauce_piment_maison_homemade_chili_sauce_gabonese', 'Sauce Piment Maison (Homemade Chili Sauce)', 38, 1.5, 7.8, 0.5, 2.5, 4.0, 30, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['sauce piment maison (homemade chili sauce)', 'mild', 'hot', 'fermented'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Homemade chili sauces prepared from fresh or dried local peppers are condiments found on every Gabonese table. Recipes vary by region and family tradition.', TRUE),
('aubergine_grillee_grilled_eggplant_gabonese', 'Aubergine Grillée (Grilled Eggplant)', 35, 0.9, 8.7, 0.2, 2.5, 3.2, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['aubergine grillée (grilled eggplant)', 'whole grilled', 'as purée'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Whole eggplants grilled over charcoal until charred and soft are used as a side dish or pureed into a smoky spread. This preparation has become popular in Libreville urban cooking.', TRUE),
('haricots_rouges_braises_braised_red_beans_gabonese', 'Haricots Rouges Braisés (Braised Red Beans)', 127, 7.8, 22.8, 0.5, 6.5, 0.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['haricots rouges braisés (braised red beans)', 'with tomato', 'plain', 'with palm oil'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Red kidney beans slowly braised with tomatoes, onions, and spices are a filling and nutritious side dish in Gabon. They are eaten alongside rice or with baguette.', TRUE),
('lentilles_cuisinees_cooked_lentils_gabonese', 'Lentilles Cuisinées (Cooked Lentils)', 116, 9.0, 20.1, 0.4, 7.9, 1.8, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['lentilles cuisinées (cooked lentils)', 'with onions', 'with tomato', 'plain'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Lentils have been adopted in urban Gabonese cooking and are prepared as a savory side dish with onions and herbs. They are valued for their protein content and affordability.', TRUE),
('epinards_au_lait_de_coco_gabonese', 'Épinards au Lait de Coco', 98, 3.2, 7.5, 7.0, 2.8, 2.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['épinards au lait de coco', 'with garlic', 'with chili'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Spinach or local greens cooked in coconut milk with garlic and spices is a creamy side dish with coastal roots, reflecting the influence of Atlantic trade routes on Gabonese cuisine.', TRUE),
('feuilles_de_manioc_au_lait_de_coco_gabonese', 'Feuilles de Manioc au Lait de Coco', 95, 4.5, 8.5, 6.5, 3.0, 2.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['feuilles de manioc au lait de coco', 'with garlic', 'with fish'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Pounded cassava leaves cooked in coconut milk rather than palm oil is a coastal variation found in Libreville and estuarine communities, offering a lighter and sweeter flavor profile.', TRUE),
('choux_braises_braised_cabbage_gabonese', 'Choux Braisés (Braised Cabbage)', 42, 2.0, 7.8, 1.5, 3.0, 4.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['choux braisés (braised cabbage)', 'with tomato', 'plain braised', 'with carrot'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Braised cabbage with onions, tomatoes, and seasoning is a simple everyday vegetable side dish in Gabon. White and green cabbage are both available in markets throughout the country.', TRUE),
('salade_nicoise_adaptee_gabonese', 'Salade Niçoise Adaptée', 145, 8.5, 10.5, 8.0, 2.5, 2.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['salade niçoise adaptée', 'with anchovies', 'without anchovies'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'An adapted Niçoise salad with canned tuna, green beans, tomatoes, and eggs reflects Gabon''s strong French culinary heritage and is served in upscale restaurants and bistros.', TRUE),
('avocat_en_salade_gabonese', 'Avocat en Salade', 160, 2.0, 9.0, 14.7, 6.7, 0.7, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['avocat en salade', 'with tomato', 'plain with lemon', 'with vinaigrette'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Diced avocado with lemon juice, onions, and tomatoes is a refreshing salad popular in Gabon where avocado trees grow abundantly. It is eaten as a side dish or light lunch.', TRUE),
('ananas_frais_tranche_fresh_sliced_pineapple_gabonese', 'Ananas Frais Tranché (Fresh Sliced Pineapple)', 50, 0.5, 13.1, 0.1, 1.4, 9.9, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['ananas frais tranché (fresh sliced pineapple)', 'plain', 'with chili salt', 'juiced'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Fresh pineapple grown in Gabon is served sliced as a palate cleanser, side fruit, or dessert. Gabon''s climate produces exceptionally sweet pineapples valued throughout Central Africa.', TRUE),
('banane_douce_fraiche_fresh_sweet_banana_gabonese', 'Banane Douce Fraîche (Fresh Sweet Banana)', 89, 1.1, 22.8, 0.3, 2.6, 12.2, 120, 120, 'research', ARRAY['banane douce fraîche (fresh sweet banana)', 'small local variety', 'large variety', 'baby banana'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sweet bananas are consumed as everyday snacks and sides throughout Gabon. Multiple local varieties with different sizes and sweetness levels are sold at every market.', TRUE),
('salade_de_fruits_tropicaux_gabonese', 'Salade de Fruits Tropicaux', 62, 0.8, 15.5, 0.3, 2.0, 12.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['salade de fruits tropicaux', 'with lime juice', 'with coconut', 'with honey'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Mixed tropical fruit salads combining mango, pineapple, papaya, banana, and citrus are served as refreshing desserts and sides in Gabonese homes and restaurants.', TRUE),
('pain_brioche_gabonese', 'Pain Brioche', 345, 8.5, 48.0, 14.0, 1.5, 10.5, 80, 40, 'research', ARRAY['pain brioche', 'plain', 'with raisins', 'individual rolls'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Buttery brioche bread is baked in Libreville patisseries and sold as a breakfast treat or base for sweet preparations. Its rich texture reflects Gabon''s French pastry traditions.', TRUE),
('croissant_gabonese', 'Croissant', 406, 8.2, 45.6, 21.0, 1.8, 5.0, 60, 60, 'research', ARRAY['croissant', 'plain', 'with butter', 'with chocolate'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Croissants are produced by patisseries in Libreville and major cities, a direct legacy of French colonial pastry culture. They are consumed at breakfast with butter and jam.', TRUE),
('pain_au_chocolat_gabonese', 'Pain au Chocolat', 422, 7.5, 50.0, 22.5, 2.0, 18.0, 70, 70, 'research', ARRAY['pain au chocolat', 'with dark chocolate', 'with milk chocolate'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Pain au chocolat is available in Libreville patisseries and is a popular breakfast pastry reflecting the deep French culinary influence that persists in Gabonese urban food culture.', TRUE),
('gateau_yaourt_yogurt_cake_gabonese', 'Gâteau Yaourt (Yogurt Cake)', 295, 5.5, 42.0, 12.0, 0.8, 22.0, 80, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['gâteau yaourt (yogurt cake)', 'plain', 'with vanilla', 'with citrus zest'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'The classic French yogurt cake, made using the yogurt container as a measuring cup, is baked in Gabonese homes and is often the first cake taught to children, symbolizing everyday baking culture.', TRUE),
('galettes_de_mais_corn_cakes_gabonese', 'Galettes de Maïs (Corn Cakes)', 210, 4.5, 38.0, 4.8, 2.2, 3.0, 100, 50, 'research', ARRAY['galettes de maïs (corn cakes)', 'plain', 'with spices', 'sweet version'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Corn-based flat cakes fried or griddled on a hot surface are a traditional Gabonese snack and side dish, made from ground maize mixed with water and salt.', TRUE),
('gateau_de_patate_douce_sweet_potato_cake_gabonese', 'Gâteau de Patate Douce (Sweet Potato Cake)', 185, 3.0, 35.5, 4.0, 2.5, 15.0, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['gâteau de patate douce (sweet potato cake)', 'plain', 'with cinnamon', 'with coconut'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sweet potato is mashed and mixed with flour, egg, and sugar to make a dense, moist cake that serves as both a snack and dessert in Gabonese communities.', TRUE),
('igname_pilee_pounded_yam_gabonese', 'Igname Pilée (Pounded Yam)', 118, 1.5, 27.5, 0.2, 4.1, 0.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['igname pilée (pounded yam)', 'plain', 'with palm oil dip'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Boiled yam pounded in a mortar until smooth and stretchy, igname pilée is the ceremonial pounded starch of Gabon''s interior communities, served with savory soups and sauces.', TRUE),
('ntoba_mbodi_cooked_pumpkin_gabonese', 'Ntoba Mbodi (Cooked Pumpkin)', 45, 1.2, 10.5, 0.2, 0.5, 4.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['ntoba mbodi (cooked pumpkin)', 'boiled', 'roasted', 'in stew'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Boiled or steamed pumpkin is eaten as a sweet vegetable side dish in Gabon. It is also added to stews and porridges where its natural sweetness balances savory flavors.', TRUE),
('chou_fleur_saute_sauteed_cauliflower_gabonese', 'Chou-Fleur Sauté (Sautéed Cauliflower)', 55, 2.5, 8.5, 2.0, 3.0, 3.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['chou-fleur sauté (sautéed cauliflower)', 'plain sauté', 'with tomato', 'gratin style'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sautéed cauliflower with garlic and oil is prepared in urban Gabonese households and restaurants. Cauliflower is imported and available in supermarkets in Libreville.', TRUE),
('brocoli_a_lail_gabonese', 'Brocoli à l''Ail', 50, 3.0, 7.5, 1.8, 2.6, 2.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['brocoli à l''ail', 'with garlic', 'steamed', 'with lemon'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Broccoli sautéed with garlic is found in upscale restaurants and expat-influenced home cooking in Gabon. It reflects the international culinary influences present in Libreville.', TRUE),
('poireaux_braises_braised_leeks_gabonese', 'Poireaux Braisés (Braised Leeks)', 61, 1.5, 14.2, 0.3, 1.8, 3.9, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['poireaux braisés (braised leeks)', 'with butter', 'with vinaigrette', 'plain'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Braised leeks prepared French-style with butter and salt are found in French-influenced home cooking in Gabon. Leeks are imported and sold in supermarkets catering to urban consumers.', TRUE),
('courgette_sautee_sauteed_zucchini_gabonese', 'Courgette Sautée (Sautéed Zucchini)', 32, 1.2, 5.8, 1.0, 1.0, 3.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['courgette sautée (sautéed zucchini)', 'with herbs', 'plain', 'with tomato'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sautéed zucchini with herbs and garlic is prepared in French-influenced Gabonese cooking and is popular in urban restaurants and expatriate households.', TRUE),
('salade_cesar_adaptee_gabonese', 'Salade César Adaptée', 175, 9.0, 11.0, 11.5, 1.5, 2.0, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['salade césar adaptée', 'with chicken', 'plain', 'with anchovies'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Caesar salad adapted to local ingredients, with romaine lettuce, croutons, and Parmesan, is served in upscale Libreville restaurants catering to expatriates and affluent Gabonese.', TRUE),
('salade_de_riz_rice_salad_gabonese', 'Salade de Riz (Rice Salad)', 145, 3.0, 28.5, 3.0, 1.5, 2.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['salade de riz (rice salad)', 'with tuna', 'with vegetables', 'with chicken'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cold rice salad mixed with vegetables, tuna, or chicken and dressed with vinaigrette is a popular make-ahead lunch and picnic dish in urban Gabonese households.', TRUE),
('salade_de_pates_pasta_salad_gabonese', 'Salade de Pâtes (Pasta Salad)', 185, 5.5, 32.0, 4.5, 2.0, 3.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['salade de pâtes (pasta salad)', 'with mayonnaise', 'with vinaigrette', 'with tuna'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cold pasta salad with vegetables and a vinaigrette or mayonnaise dressing has become popular in Gabon for buffets and family gatherings, reflecting urban food modernization.', TRUE),
('concombre_a_la_creme_creamed_cucumber_gabonese', 'Concombre à la Crème (Creamed Cucumber)', 45, 0.8, 5.0, 2.5, 0.5, 2.8, 120, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['concombre à la crème (creamed cucumber)', 'with dill', 'with garlic', 'plain cream'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cucumber slices in a creamy yogurt or crème fraîche dressing with dill is a French-inspired side salad found in Gabonese upscale dining establishments.', TRUE),
('betterave_en_salade_beet_salad_gabonese', 'Betterave en Salade (Beet Salad)', 58, 1.7, 13.0, 0.2, 2.8, 9.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['betterave en salade (beet salad)', 'with vinaigrette', 'with onion', 'with cream'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cooked beet sliced and dressed with vinaigrette is a classic French side salad available in Gabonese supermarkets as a prepared food and made from scratch in home cooking.', TRUE),
('celeri_remoulade_gabonese', 'Céleri Rémoulade', 95, 1.5, 10.5, 5.5, 1.8, 3.5, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['céleri rémoulade', 'classic', 'light'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Celeriac rémoulade, grated raw celery root in mustard mayonnaise, is a quintessentially French side salad found in Gabonese patisseries and traiteur shops in Libreville.', TRUE),
('taboule_tabbouleh_gabonese', 'Taboulé (Tabbouleh)', 115, 3.0, 18.0, 4.5, 2.8, 2.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['taboulé (tabbouleh)', 'with bulgur', 'with couscous', 'with quinoa'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Tabbouleh made with bulgur wheat, parsley, tomatoes, and lemon juice is popular in Gabonese cities, introduced through Lebanese and North African diaspora communities.', TRUE),
('couscous_nature_plain_couscous_gabonese', 'Couscous Nature (Plain Couscous)', 175, 6.0, 36.0, 0.6, 2.2, 0.4, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['couscous nature (plain couscous)', 'plain', 'with butter', 'with harissa'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Plain steamed couscous is available in Gabon through North African influence and is served as a simple starchy side dish or as a base for vegetable and meat stews.', TRUE),
('pates_sautees_aux_legumes_gabonese', 'Pâtes Sautées aux Légumes', 180, 6.0, 32.5, 3.5, 2.8, 3.0, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['pâtes sautées aux légumes', 'with tomato sauce', 'plain sauté', 'with vegetables'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Pasta sautéed with vegetables and oil is a quick everyday dish in urban Gabonese households. Pasta has been widely adopted as an accessible and versatile starchy staple.', TRUE),
('galettes_de_pomme_de_terre_potato_pancakes_gabonese', 'Galettes de Pomme de Terre (Potato Pancakes)', 215, 3.5, 28.0, 10.0, 2.5, 1.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['galettes de pomme de terre (potato pancakes)', 'plain', 'with onion', 'with herbs'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Grated potato patties fried until crispy are a European-influenced preparation found in Gabonese urban cooking, served as a side dish or snack at family gatherings.', TRUE),
('mayonnaise_maison_gabonese', 'Mayonnaise Maison', 680, 1.5, 0.6, 75.0, 0.0, 0.3, 15, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['mayonnaise maison', 'plain', 'with garlic (aïoli)', 'with herbs'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Homemade mayonnaise prepared from egg yolks and oil is a French culinary tradition maintained in Gabonese cooking, used as a condiment, salad dressing, and sandwich spread.', TRUE),
('vinaigrette_maison_gabonese', 'Vinaigrette Maison', 270, 0.2, 2.5, 28.5, 0.0, 1.5, 15, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['vinaigrette maison', 'with dijon mustard', 'with lemon', 'with herbs'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Classic French vinaigrette with mustard, vinegar, and oil is the standard salad dressing in Gabonese French-influenced cuisine, made fresh in homes and restaurants.', TRUE),
('huile_de_palme_raffinee_gabonese', 'Huile de Palme Raffinée', 884, 0.0, 0.0, 100.0, 0.0, 0.0, 10, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['huile de palme raffinée', 'red (unrefined)', 'refined yellow'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Refined palm oil is the primary cooking fat in Gabon, used across all types of dishes from frying to saucing. It is produced domestically and is central to Gabonese culinary identity.', TRUE),
('noix_de_coco_rapee_grated_coconut_gabonese', 'Noix de Coco Râpée (Grated Coconut)', 354, 3.3, 15.2, 33.5, 9.0, 6.2, 40, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['noix de coco râpée (grated coconut)', 'fresh', 'dried', 'toasted'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Freshly grated coconut is used in baking, desserts, and savory coconut-based dishes in coastal Gabon. Vendors selling freshly grated coconut are common in Libreville markets.', TRUE),
('lait_de_coco_coconut_milk_gabonese', 'Lait de Coco (Coconut Milk)', 197, 2.1, 5.5, 20.2, 2.2, 3.3, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['lait de coco (coconut milk)', 'thick (first press)', 'thin (second press)', 'canned'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Coconut milk pressed from grated fresh coconut is used extensively in coastal Gabonese cooking for curries, soups, rice dishes, and desserts. It adds a distinctive tropical richness.', TRUE),
('graines_de_sesame_sesame_seeds_gabonese', 'Graines de Sésame (Sesame Seeds)', 573, 17.7, 23.5, 49.7, 11.8, 0.3, 15, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['graines de sésame (sesame seeds)', 'white', 'black', 'toasted'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sesame seeds are used as a garnish and ingredient in Gabonese cooking, sprinkled on breads and incorporated into sauces. They are sold in small quantities at local markets.', TRUE),
('cacahuetes_grillees_roasted_peanuts_gabonese', 'Cacahuètes Grillées (Roasted Peanuts)', 567, 25.8, 16.1, 49.2, 8.5, 4.7, 30, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['cacahuètes grillées (roasted peanuts)', 'salted', 'plain', 'spiced'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Roasted peanuts are ubiquitous snacks sold by vendors throughout Gabon and are also crushed into paste for use in soups and sauces. They are a fundamental ingredient in Central African cooking.', TRUE),
('noix_du_gabon_noix_de_safou_african_pear_gabonese', 'Noix du Gabon / Noix de Safou (African Pear)', 338, 4.6, 5.4, 35.4, 3.0, 2.0, 100, 30, 'research', ARRAY['noix du gabon / noix de safou (african pear)', 'boiled', 'roasted over fire'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Safou, the African pear or bush butter fruit, is a uniquely beloved Gabonese fruit boiled in salted water until soft. Its buttery, starchy flesh is eaten as a side dish or snack.', TRUE),
('mangue_verte_en_salade_green_mango_salad_gabonese', 'Mangue Verte en Salade (Green Mango Salad)', 60, 0.8, 15.5, 0.4, 1.6, 8.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['mangue verte en salade (green mango salad)', 'with chili', 'with salt', 'with palm oil'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Unripe green mango shredded or diced and dressed with salt, chili, and lime is a tangy refreshing side dish enjoyed in Gabon. The sourness is a pleasant contrast to rich main dishes.', TRUE),
('tomates_cerises_en_salade_cherry_tomato_salad_gabonese', 'Tomates Cerises en Salade (Cherry Tomato Salad)', 27, 1.3, 5.8, 0.3, 1.2, 3.9, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['tomates cerises en salade (cherry tomato salad)', 'with basil', 'with onion', 'with mozzarella'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cherry tomatoes halved with fresh herbs and vinaigrette constitute a modern side salad popular in Libreville cafés and homes influenced by contemporary French cuisine.', TRUE),
('ufs_mimosa_deviled_eggs_gabonese', 'Œufs Mimosa (Deviled Eggs)', 175, 12.5, 1.5, 12.8, 0.0, 0.5, 100, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['œufs mimosa (deviled eggs)', 'with paprika', 'with herbs', 'with capers'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'French-style deviled eggs filled with a yolk, mayonnaise, and mustard mixture are served as appetizers and side dishes at Gabonese gatherings and celebrations.', TRUE),
('gratin_de_courgette_gabonese', 'Gratin de Courgette', 125, 5.5, 9.0, 8.0, 1.5, 3.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['gratin de courgette', 'with béchamel', 'with tomato', 'with cheese'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Baked zucchini gratin with béchamel and cheese is a French-inspired baked side dish found in Gabonese households and restaurants with wood or gas ovens.', TRUE),
('gratin_dauphinois_gabonese', 'Gratin Dauphinois', 180, 4.5, 16.5, 11.0, 1.8, 2.0, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['gratin dauphinois', 'with garlic', 'with cheese', 'light version'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Potato gratin with cream and garlic is a French classic prepared in Gabonese homes and French restaurants in Libreville. It represents the enduring influence of French haute cuisine.', TRUE),
('quiche_lorraine_gabonese', 'Quiche Lorraine', 268, 9.5, 17.5, 19.0, 0.8, 2.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['quiche lorraine', 'classic lorraine', 'vegetarian', 'with salmon'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Quiche Lorraine with bacon and Gruyère in a buttery crust is baked in Libreville patisseries and served as a lunch dish or snack, reflecting French gastronomy''s deep roots in Gabon.', TRUE),
('tarte_aux_legumes_vegetable_tart_gabonese', 'Tarte aux Légumes (Vegetable Tart)', 230, 7.0, 22.5, 13.5, 2.5, 3.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['tarte aux légumes (vegetable tart)', 'with leek', 'with tomato', 'with zucchini'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Savory vegetable tarts made with seasonal vegetables in a pastry shell are prepared in French-style patisseries and upscale restaurants in Libreville.', TRUE),
('chaussons_aux_legumes_vegetable_turnovers_gabonese', 'Chaussons aux Légumes (Vegetable Turnovers)', 275, 6.5, 30.0, 14.5, 2.5, 3.0, 120, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['chaussons aux légumes (vegetable turnovers)', 'with spinach', 'with mixed vegetables', 'with cheese'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Pastry turnovers filled with vegetables are sold in Gabonese bakeries and served as snacks or light lunches. They combine French pastry technique with local vegetable fillings.', TRUE),
('boulettes_de_riz_rice_balls_gabonese', 'Boulettes de Riz (Rice Balls)', 145, 3.0, 32.0, 0.5, 0.8, 0.2, 150, 60, 'research', ARRAY['boulettes de riz (rice balls)', 'plain', 'with herbs', 'with sesame'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Compact balls of cooked rice seasoned with salt are a convenient portable food eaten at picnics and on journeys in Gabon. They are also served as a side dish with sauces.', TRUE),
('batonnets_de_manioc_frits_fried_cassava_sticks_gabonese', 'Bâtonnets de Manioc Frits (Fried Cassava Sticks)', 295, 2.2, 48.5, 10.5, 2.0, 1.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['bâtonnets de manioc frits (fried cassava sticks)', 'plain', 'seasoned', 'with chili sauce'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cassava cut into sticks and deep-fried until crispy are served as a side dish alternative to French fries throughout Gabon. They are crispy on the outside and fluffy within.', TRUE),
('alloco_fried_ripe_plantain_gabonese', 'Alloco (Fried Ripe Plantain)', 163, 1.2, 34.0, 4.5, 2.5, 15.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['alloco (fried ripe plantain)', 'with hot pepper sauce', 'plain', 'with grilled fish'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Alloco, slices of ripe plantain deep-fried in palm oil until caramelized and golden, is one of the most beloved side dishes across West and Central Africa including Gabon.', TRUE),
('taro_frit_fried_taro_gabonese', 'Taro Frit (Fried Taro)', 175, 2.0, 35.5, 4.0, 4.0, 1.5, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['taro frit (fried taro)', 'thin sliced', 'thick sliced', 'with salt'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Sliced taro root fried in palm oil until golden and crispy is a filling starchy side dish popular in Gabonese households as an alternative to cassava or plantain preparations.', TRUE),
('epis_de_mais_grilles_grilled_corn_on_the_cob_gabonese', 'Épis de Maïs Grillés (Grilled Corn on the Cob)', 86, 3.2, 19.0, 1.2, 2.7, 6.3, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['épis de maïs grillés (grilled corn on the cob)', 'plain grilled', 'with butter', 'with chili salt'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Corn cobs grilled over charcoal are sold by roadside vendors throughout Gabon and eaten as snacks or side dishes. Grilled corn with a pinch of salt is a childhood favorite.', TRUE),
('miel_local_local_honey_gabonese', 'Miel Local (Local Honey)', 304, 0.3, 82.4, 0.0, 0.2, 82.1, 20, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['miel local (local honey)', 'forest honey', 'plantation honey'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Wild honey harvested by traditional beekeepers in Gabon''s forests is prized for its complex flavor. It is used as a sweetener for teas, spread on bread, and used in traditional medicine.', TRUE),
('confiture_tropicale_tropical_fruit_jam_gabonese', 'Confiture Tropicale (Tropical Fruit Jam)', 250, 0.4, 65.0, 0.1, 0.5, 62.0, 20, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['confiture tropicale (tropical fruit jam)', 'mango', 'pineapple', 'guava', 'passion fruit'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Homemade jams from mango, pineapple, guava, and passion fruit are prepared in Gabonese households and small artisan operations. They are spread on baguettes and brioche for breakfast.', TRUE),
('puree_de_patate_douce_gabonese', 'Purée de Patate Douce', 105, 2.0, 24.5, 0.2, 3.0, 8.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['purée de patate douce', 'plain', 'with butter', 'with coconut milk'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Mashed sweet potato seasoned simply with salt or a touch of butter is a naturally sweet side dish popular with children and adults in Gabon, especially during the sweet potato harvest season.', TRUE),
('puree_de_manioc_gabonese', 'Purée de Manioc', 155, 1.4, 38.5, 0.3, 2.0, 1.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['purée de manioc', 'plain', 'with butter', 'with palm oil'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Smooth cassava mash prepared by boiling and pureeing cassava root is a softer alternative to fufu for soups and stews. It is especially popular for young children and elderly people.', TRUE),
('foutou_de_plantain_gabonese', 'Foutou de Plantain', 130, 1.3, 33.5, 0.5, 2.5, 5.0, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['foutou de plantain', 'plain', 'mixed with cassava'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Plantain foutou is made by boiling and pounding green plantains into a smooth, dense dough eaten with soups and stews. It is softer and slightly sweeter than yam foutou.', TRUE),
('farine_de_mais_grillee_roasted_corn_flour_gabonese', 'Farine de Maïs Grillée (Roasted Corn Flour)', 370, 8.5, 76.0, 4.5, 7.2, 2.0, 50, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['farine de maïs grillée (roasted corn flour)', 'with water', 'with milk', 'with sugar'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Roasted corn flour mixed with water or milk is eaten as a quick porridge-style snack or drink. It is a traditional convenience food that provides sustained energy for outdoor workers.', TRUE),
('crudites_assortiment_gabonese', 'Crudités Assortiment', 35, 1.5, 7.5, 0.3, 2.5, 4.0, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['crudités assortiment', 'with vinaigrette', 'with mayonnaise dip', 'plain'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'A platter of raw vegetables including carrot sticks, cucumber slices, tomatoes, and radishes served with a dip is a French-influenced appetizer and side dish served in Libreville restaurants.', TRUE),
('semoule_au_beurre_buttered_semolina_gabonese', 'Semoule au Beurre (Buttered Semolina)', 175, 5.5, 32.5, 4.0, 2.0, 0.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['semoule au beurre (buttered semolina)', 'with butter', 'plain', 'with herbs'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Fine semolina cooked with water and finished with butter is served as a side starch in French-influenced Gabonese cooking. It is a lighter alternative to heavy traditional starches.', TRUE),
('polenta_mais_gabonese', 'Polenta Maïs', 105, 2.5, 22.5, 1.2, 1.5, 0.5, 200, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['polenta maïs', 'soft', 'grilled', 'with cheese'], 'fusion', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Cornmeal polenta has been adopted into Gabonese cooking as a smooth, comforting side dish served with saucy meat and vegetable dishes. It is an affordable and versatile carbohydrate.', TRUE),
('ndongo_pumpkin_seed_paste_gabonese', 'Ndongo (Pumpkin Seed Paste)', 525, 20.0, 18.0, 45.0, 5.5, 2.0, 50, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['ndongo (pumpkin seed paste)', 'plain', 'in vegetable sauce', 'with spices'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Ground pumpkin seeds made into a thick paste are used as a protein-rich sauce base in Gabonese traditional cooking. It is stirred into vegetable dishes to add body and flavor.', TRUE),
('feuilles_de_gboma_gboma_leaves_gabonese', 'Feuilles de Gboma (Gboma Leaves)', 38, 3.5, 5.8, 0.6, 2.2, 0.8, 150, NULL, 'research', ARRAY['feuilles de gboma (gboma leaves)', 'with palm oil', 'with smoked fish'], 'traditional', NULL, 1, 'GA', 'Gboma leaves (a type of local eggplant plant greens) are cooked in palm oil with smoked fish and spices in Gabonese and broader Central African cuisine. They have a distinctive slightly bitter flavor.', TRUE),
